==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Swathe
<hw>Swathe</hw> <pr>(sw⟦amac⟧⟦th⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Swathed</conjf>
<pr>(sw⟦amac⟧⟦th⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Swathing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>swathen</ets>, AS.
<ets>swe⟦edh⟧ain</ets>. See <er>Swath</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, and cf.
<er>Swaddle</er>.]</ety> <def>To bind with a swathe, band, bandage, or
rollers.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their children are never <qex>swathed</qex> or bound about with
any thing when they are first born.</q> <rj><qau>Abp.
Abbot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swathe</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Swathe
<hw>Swathe</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A bandage; a band; a
swath.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wrapped me in above an hundred yards of <qex>swathe</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Milk and a <qex>swathe</qex>, at first, his whole demand.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The solemn glory of the afternoon, with its long
<qex>swathes</qex> of light between the far off rows of limes.</q>
<rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Swather</ent>⟦br⟧
